<font color="#FF0000">RAINBOWS, SADNESS, THE PRESENT</font><br>
<tt>Sat Nov  1  8:22:15 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cookie Jar,<br><br>
No *answers* are necessary, we know you are getting soft in your old age. When you coming to Tennessee? Come next spring. Lots of histroy in this little place. We can plant pumpkin seeds and chase rainbows.<br><br>
Next weekend I will travel to DC for Veterans Day. Will visit the Vietnam Veterans Memorial with heavy regrets about the 58,000 who never got the chance to plant a garden, see their children grow, nor marvel at the technological advances we now take for granted.<br><br>
I contacted the mother of one of my friends who was killed by a booby trap. I sent her a letter, not sure if she was Jerry's relation or not. Three nights later I received a phone call from her. Indeed, she was Jerry's mom. I could tell that she was holding back the sobs as she told of how grateful she was that I had tried to find her. In my letter I had <br>
said that her burden was my burden for many years, I wanted her to know that she was not alone in her grief.<br><br>
She related how she had lost a grandson killed in a farming accident. He was a teeneager. Her farm had been destroyed in a tornado several years back. Somehow, I sensed in this woman, great determination.<br><br>
I am reading a book by Bernard Fall called _Hell In A Very Small Place_. Fall is better known for his book _A Street Without Joy_.<br><br>
The book I am reading is about the battle at Dien Bien Phu. Did you know that the French forces that parachuted into Dien Bien Phu in the beginning were approximately 1/2 Vietnamese? John Paul Vann, in the book _A Bright Shining Lie_ vigorously campaigned for the same. Vietnamese incorporated into American units. Early in the war he maintained that the war could not be won using american troops. Harkins and Westy would have none of it. Odd how Khe Sanh is reminiscent of Dien Bien Phu.<br><br>
Anyway, that is what I am doing these days - trying to become a student of the war in which I played a role, yet which I am unfamiliar with in many ways.
